{{Other people|Mark Bell}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Use British English|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians --> | name = Mark Bell | image = Mark_Bell_(LFO)_on_stage_in_Moscow.JPG | caption = Mark Bell on stage in Arma 17, Moscow, on 30 March 2013. | occupation = {{hlist|DJ|record producer}} | instrument = {{hlist|[[Synthesizer]]|[[Turntablism|turntables]]}} | years_active = 1988–2014 | label = [[Warp (record label)|Warp]] |associated_acts = {{hlist|[[LFO (British band)|LFO]]|[[Björk]]|[[Depeche Mode]]}} | background = non_vocal_instrumentalist | birth_date = {{birth date|1971|2|22}} | death_date = {{death date|2014|10|8|df=yes}} }}
'''Mark Bell''' was a British DJ and record producer of [[house music]] who, as well as being a member of the pioneering electronic music group [[LFO (British band)|LFO]]<ref name="HawkinsScott2012">{{cite book|last1=Hawkins|first1=Stan|last2=Scott|first2=Derek B.|title=Critical Musicological Reflections: Essays in Honour of Derek B. Scott|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3UrMpU2v8u8C&pg=PA99|accessdate=5 September 2014|year=2012|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=9781409425618|pages=99–}}</ref> on [[Warp Records]], collaborated with a wide range of artists such as [[Björk]] and [[Depeche Mode]], for whom he took on the production duties for the entire ''[[Exciter (album)|Exciter]]'' album.
==Biography== ===Early life=== Mark Bell's early musical influences came from three specific sources.<ref name="warp-bio">{{cite web|url=http://warp.net/news/2003-biography-by-bill-brewster/|publisher=[[Warp (record label)|Warp]]|title=LFO|first=Bill|last=Brewster|date=16 December 2008|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> One was an art teacher in school who taught art and played music by [[Jean-Michel Jarre]] and [[Kraftwerk]], an older sister who played [[disco music|disco]], [[funk music]] and [[Electro (music)|electro]] from her bedroom, and a music shop in [[Leeds]] Mark described as having "arcade games like ''[[Tempest (video game)|Tempest]]'' and ''[[Defender (video game)|Defender]]''" and that it would play "loads of early hip hop like [[Schoolly D]]. I remember feeling this is mine and my friend’s place".<ref name="warp-bio" /> Bell first experiments in electronic music involved him making a deal with his girlfriend's father who made his musical ballads listened to despite disliking them.<ref name="warp-bio" /> Bell convinced him he required a real backing band and purchased his drum machine from him.<ref name="warp-bio" />
Bell went to college to study photography and graphic design, where he met the West Yorkshire DJ Martin Williams and [[Gez Varley]].<ref name="warp-bio" /> With money from Varley's grandmother, Bell had access to a bedroom full of equipment.<ref name="warp-bio" /> In 1988, Varley, Bell and Martin began to play gigs as [[LFO (British band)|LFO]], named after the [[Low-frequency oscillation|low frequency oscillator]], a function of many synthesizers.<ref name="warp-bio" /><ref name="rs-death">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/bjork-depeche-mode-producer-mark-bell-dead-20141013|work=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]|title=Bjork, Depeche Mode Producer Mark Bell Dead|accessdate=8 February 2018|last=Kreps|first=Daneil|date=13 October 2014}}</ref>
===LFO=== LFO were performing at the Warehouse, a club in [[Leeds]], when Steve Beckett and Rob Mitchell arrived and noticed the positive reception club goers had to the track "LFO".<ref name="warp-bio" /> Beckett and Mitchell were the original creators of the [[Warp (record label)|Warp]] record label, but had not officially created the label yet.<ref name="warp-bio" /> Despite this, Beckett and Mitchell offered to put out a 12-inch single,<ref name="warp-bio" /> which was expected to sell about 2,000 copies but eventually became a Top 20 hit.<ref name="rs-death" /> The label released their first studio album ''[[Frequencies (album)|Frequencies]]'' in 1991.<ref name="warp-bio" /> Following the album's release, Bell continued to release singles for other independent labels such as [[Carl Craig]]'s [[Planet E]].<ref name="warp-bio" /> [[File:Björk at Cannes.jpg|thumb|Mark Bell would perform production duties on all of Björk's albums between ''Homogenic'' and ''Biophilia''.]] While working on a follow-up album, Bell began his partnership with [[Björk]] before the release of her album ''[[Post (Björk album)|Post]]''.{{sfn|Pytlik|2003|p=181}} Bell gave her a cassette of LFO demo material allowing her to use what she wanted for a future release.{{sfn|Pytlik|2003|p=181}} Björk chose a track that would later become her song "I Go Humble", which would show up again in instrumental form as "Shove Piggy Shove" on the LFO album ''[[Advance (album)|Advance]]'' in 1996.<ref name="warp-bio" />{{sfn|Pytlik|2003|p=181}} When asked about the long gap between records, Bell stated “It’s not intentional...It's easy doing your first album as you have all the first part of your life to express. The second one is harder unless you're going to repeat yourself... and repetition bores me a bit, it's a complete wasted opportunity to be creative."<ref name="warp-bio" /> After the release of ''Advance'', Bell and Varley parted ways, with Bell retaining rights to the name LFO.<ref name="warp-bio" /> Bell continued to perform under the LFO moniker.<ref name="warp-bio" /><ref name="rs-death" />
===Production work and final LFO album===
Björk had initially wanted Bell to contribute to her albums ''Debut'' and ''Post'' and started a real collaboration with her on the album ''[[Homogenic]]''.<ref name="rs-death" /><ref name=milkfactory>{{cite web|title=Mark Bell / LFO Interview |work=The Milk Factory |url=http://www.themilkfactory.co.uk/interviews/lfoiw.htm |accessdate=2009-07-05 |date=June 2002 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091015020932/http://www.themilkfactory.co.uk/interviews/lfoiw.htm |archivedate=2009-10-15 }}</ref> Bell was credited for the majority of the album's production, including the songs "[[Pluto (song)|Pluto]]", "[[Alarm Call]]", and the bassline in "[[Jóga]]".{{sfn|Pytlik|2003|p=124}} Björk stated that she "trusts and respects what [Bell] does for me. If I were to say who has influenced me most it would be [[Stockhausen]], Kraftwerk, [[Brian Eno]] and Mark Bell".{{sfn|Pytlik|2003|p=124}}
Bell would also produce Björk's ''[[Selmasongs]]'', the soundtrack to the [[Lars von Trier]]'s film ''[[Dancer in the Dark]]''.<ref name="warp-bio" /> Outside Björk, Bell produced [[Depeche Mode]]'s ''[[Exciter (album)|Exciter]]''.<ref name="warp-bio" /> Bell commented on working the group was fun but strange, stating he had listened to the group when he was 12 and found the band asking him for days off or "what they should eat".<ref name="warp-bio" />
===Later works and death=== Bell released one more LFO album, ''[[Sheath (album)|Sheath]]'' in 2003.<ref name="warp-bio" /><ref name="rs-death" /> Other collaborations included contributing to [[Deltron 3030]]'s [[Deltron 3030 (album)|self-titled album]] and working on every Björk album until ''[[Biophilia (album)|Biophilia]]'' in 2011.<ref name="rs-death" />
Bell died on 8 October 2014 at the age of 43. His death was reported on 13 October 2014 due to complications after surgery.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark Bell of LFO has passed away|url=http://www.mixmag.net/news/mark-bell-of-lfo-has-passed-away|website=Mixmag|accessdate=13 October 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222203035/http://www.mixmag.net/news/mark-bell-of-lfo-has-passed-away|archivedate=22 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="RIP Mark Bell">{{cite web|last1=Jackson|first1=Glen|title=RIP Mark Bell|url=http://www.xlr8r.com/news/2014/10/rip-mark-bell|website=XLR8R|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://announce.jpress.co.uk/yorkshire-weekly-newspaper-group/obituary/mark-bell/39409975|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170301095953/http://announce.jpress.co.uk/yorkshire-weekly-newspaper-group/obituary/mark-bell/39409975|archive-date=1 March 2017|accessdate=7 February 2018|title=Mark Bell : Obituary|work=Yorkshire Weekly Newspaper Group|date=24 October 2014}}</ref>
