:''This article is about the concept in developmental biology. For [[Rupert Sheldrake]]'s concept of morphic fields, see the bibliography in his article.''
[[File:Morphogenetic.gif|thumb|''A.G.Gurwitsch analysed the embryonic development of the sea-urchin as a vector-field, as if the proliferation of cells into organs were brought about by putative external forces.'']]
In the [[developmental biology]] of the early twentieth century, a '''morphogenetic field''' is a group of [[Cell (biology)|cell]]s able to respond to discrete, localized [[biochemical]] signals leading to the [[morphogenesis|development of specific morphological structures]] or [[organ (anatomy)|organ]]s.<ref name=MBOC>{{cite book |vauthors=Alberts B, Johnson A, Lewis J, Raff M, Roberts K, Walter P | title=Universal Mechanisms of Animal Development. ''in:'' Molecular Biology of the Cell | edition=4th | publisher=Garland | year=2002 | url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/bv.fcgi?&rid=mboc4.section.3792 | isbn=0-8153-3218-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Jacobson AG, Sater AK |title=Features of embryonic induction |journal=Development |volume=104 |issue=3 |pages=341–59 |date=1 November 1988|pmid=3076860 |url=http://dev.biologists.org/cgi/reprint/104/3/341 }}</ref> The [[wikt:spatial|spatial]] and [[wikt:temporal|temporal]] extents of the embryonic field are dynamic, and within the field is a collection of interacting cells out of which a particular organ is formed.<ref name=Gilbert_1996>{{cite journal |vauthors=Gilbert SF, Opitz JM, Raff RA |title=Resynthesizing evolutionary and developmental biology |journal=Dev. Biol. |volume=173 |issue=2 |pages=357–72 |year=1996 |pmid=8605997 |doi=10.1006/dbio.1996.0032}}</ref> As a group, the cells within a given morphogenetic field are constrained: thus, cells in a ''limb field'' will become a limb tissue, those in a ''[[cardiac]] field'' will become heart tissue.<ref name=Gilbert_2003>{{cite book |author=Gilbert SF |title=Developmental biology |edition=7th |publisher=Sinauer Associates |location=Sunderland, Mass |year=2003 |isbn=0-87893-258-5 |pages=65–6}}</ref> However, specific cellular programming of individual cells in a field is flexible: an individual cell in a cardiac field can be redirected via cell-to-cell signaling to replace specific damaged or missing cells.<ref name=Gilbert_2003 /> [[Imaginal disc]]s in insect [[larva]]e are examples of morphogenetic fields.<ref name=MBOC2>{{cite book  |vauthors=Alberts B, etal | title=Organogenesis and the Patterning of Appendages. ''in:'' Molecular Biology of the Cell | edition=4th | publisher=Garland | year=2002 | url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/bv.fcgi?rid=mboc4.figgrp.3898 | isbn=0-8153-3218-1}}</ref>

== Historical development ==
The concept of the morphogenetic field, fundamental in the early twentieth century to the study of embryological development, was first introduced in 1910 by [[Alexander Gurvich|Alexander G. Gurwitsch]].<ref name="Beloussov_1997">{{Cite journal | title=Life of Alexander G. Gurwitsch and his relevant contribution to the theory of morphogenetic fields | first=LV | last=Beloussov | journal=International Journal of Developmental Biology | volume=41 | issue=6 | year=1997 | pages=771&ndash;779 | url=http://www.ijdb.ehu.es/web/contents.php?vol=41&issue=6&doi=9449452 }}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, with comment by SF Gilbert and JM Optiz.</ref> Experimental support was provided by [[Ross Granville Harrison]]'s experiments transplanting fragments of a newt embryo into different locations.<ref>{{Cite journal | url=http://dev.biologists.org/cgi/reprint/112/3/669.pdf | title=Gradient fields and homeobox genes | first1=EM | last1=de Robertis | first2=EA | last2=Morita | first3=KWY | last3=Cho | journal=Development | year=1991 | volume=112 | pages=669&ndash;678 | pmid=1682124 | issue=3}}</ref>

Harrison was able to identify "fields" of cells producing organs such as limbs, tail and gills and to show that these fields could be fragmented or have undifferentiated cells added and a complete normal final structure would still result. It was thus considered that it was the "field" of cells, rather than individual cells, that were patterned for subsequent development of particular organs. The field concept was developed further by Harrison's friend [[Hans Spemann]], and then by [[Paul Alfred Weiss|Paul Weiss]] and others.<ref name="Gilbert_1996"/> The concept was similar to the meaning of the term [[entelechy]] of vitalists like [[Hans Adolf Eduard Driesch]] (1867-1941).

By the 1930s, however, the work of geneticists, especially [[Thomas Hunt Morgan]], revealed the importance of chromosomes and genes for controlling development, and the rise of the [[Modern synthesis (20th century)|new synthesis]] in evolutionary biology lessened the perceived importance of the field hypothesis. Morgan was a particularly harsh critic of fields since the gene and the field were perceived as competitors for recognition as the basic unit of [[ontogeny]].<ref name="Gilbert_1996"/> With the discovery and mapping of master control genes, such as the [[homeobox]] genes the pre-eminence of genes seemed assured. But in the late twentieth century the field concept was "rediscovered" as a useful part of developmental biology. It was found, for example, that different mutations could cause the same malformations, suggesting that the mutations were affecting a complex of structures as a unit, a unit that might correspond to the field of early 20th century embryology.

Scott Gilbert proposed that the morphogenetic field is a middle ground between genes and evolution.<ref name="Gilbert_1996"/> That is, genes act upon fields, which then act upon the developing organism.<ref name="Gilbert_1996"/> Jessica Bolker described morphogenetic fields not merely as incipient structures or organs, but as dynamic entities with their own localized development processes, which are central to the emerging field of [[Evolutionary developmental biology]] ("evo-devo").<ref>{{Cite journal| title=Modularity in Development and Why It Matters to Evo-Devo | first=JA | last=Bolker | journal=American Zoologist | volume=40| issue=5 | pages=770–776 | year=2000 | url=http://icb.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/full/40/5/770| doi=10.1668/0003-1569(2000)040[0770:MIDAWI]2.0.CO;2 }}</ref> In 2005, [[Sean B. Carroll]] and colleagues mention morphogenetic fields only as a concept proposed by early embryologists to explain the finding that a forelimb bud could be transplanted and still give rise to a forelimb; they define "field" simply as "a discrete region" in an embryo.<ref name="CGW">{{cite book |last1=Carroll |first1=Sean B. |last2=Grenier |first2=Jennifer K. |last3=Weatherbee |first3=Scott D. |authorlink1=Sean B. Carroll |title=From DNA to Diversity: Molecular Genetics and the Evolution of Animal Design |date=2005 |publisher=Blackwell |isbn=978-1-4051-1950-4 |pages=20, 242 |edition=2nd}}</ref>

