{{Unreliable sources|date=January 2018}}
'''Postmortem caloricity''' is a phenomenon where the body temperature of a [[Cadaver|corpse]] rises or remains unusually high for up to 2 hours after [[death]] instead of falling.

== Cause ==
Postmortem caloricity may (more frequently) be observed in deaths resulting from [[asphyxia]]{{Citation needed|reason=This information was already present in the article, however no source was provided & no source could be found to back up the claim.|date=January 2018}}, poisonings (e.g. with [[datura]]{{Citation needed|reason=This information was already present in the article, however no source was provided & no source could be found to back up the claim.|date=January 2018}}, [[Alcohol intoxication|alcohol]], [[Strychnine poisoning|strychnine]]), [[septicemia]], [[Bacteremia|bactaeremia]], and infectious diseases ([[yellow fever]],<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1845-08-06|title=Post-Mortem Caloricity of Yellow Fever|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1056/NEJM184508060330104|journal=The Boston Medical and Surgical Journal|volume=33|issue=1|pages=14–17|doi=10.1056/nejm184508060330104|issn=0096-6762}}</ref> [[rabies]], [[rheumatic fever]], [[cholera]], [[tetanus]], [[smallpox]]), [[meningitis]], [[peritonitis]], [[nephritis]], brain stem haemorrhages (especially pontine haemorrhages), [[Intracranial injury|intracranial injuries]], [[liver abscess]]es, [[Heat stroke|sunstroke]], etc.

== Mechanism ==
Postmortem heat production is caused by biochemical and microbial activity in the dead body. The cause of postmortem caloricity varies depending on the cause of death:
* Postmortem [[glycogenolysis]] – a phenomenon beginning soon after death observed in nearly all cadavers. In an average adult, postmortem glycogenolysis can produce up to 140 calories of heat which can raise the temperature of the body by up to 2&nbsp;°C.
* Bactaeremia, septicemia, and infectious causes – heat production may be attributed to postmortem microbial activity.
* Sunstroke, and pontine haemorrhages – disruption of thermoregulation prior to death. 
* Tetanus, and strychnine – heat is produced by muscular contractions.
The corpse may also absorb heat from the environment when environmental temperature exceeds that of the body.

